8) Muscle A is paralyzed by a focal nerve lesion. What movement(s) would be affected? Choose all that apply.
That's right!  Paralysis of latissimus dorsi will affect adduction, extension and medial rotation.

Start with the glenohumeral joint abducted. Move the insertion of these muscles toward their origin (green arrow); the joint is adducted. Continue to move the insertion of these muscles toward their origin; the joint is now extended. Notice that since the fibres pull horizontally across the anterior aspect of the humerus, perpendicular to its long axis, these muscles also medially rotate the humerus. 
Having worked out these actions yourself, you will find them easier to remember when needed.
Before moving on, notice the insertion of the pectoralis major as depicted in this illustration. It, too, attaches to the anterior aspect of the proximal humerus. The intertubercular groove lies between the insertion of the pectoralis major and that of the latissimus dorsi and teres major. You will find that these muscles have some actions in common.
